03883nmm a2200541Ia 9780801455063DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979576283  a97808014550637 a10.7591/97808014550632doi  a(DE-B1597)478621  a(OCoLC)894227822  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY04a327.4009/0422231 aRathbun, Brian C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDiplomacy's Value :bCreating Security in 1920s Europe and the Contemporary Middle East /cBrian C. Rathbun. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b4 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Security Affairs0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is the value of diplomacy? How does it affect the course of foreign affairs independent of the distribution of power and foreign policy interests? Theories of international relations too often implicitly reduce the dynamics and outcomes of diplomacy to structural factors rather than the subtle qualities of negotiation. If diplomacy is an independent effect on the conduct of world politics, it has to add value, and we have to be able to show what that value is. In Diplomacy's Value, Brian C. Rathbun sets forth a comprehensive theory of diplomacy, based on his understanding that political leaders have distinct diplomatic styles—coercive bargaining, reasoned dialogue, and pragmatic statecraft.Drawing on work in the psychology of negotiation, Rathbun explains how diplomatic styles are a function of the psychological attributes of leaders and the party coalitions they represent. The combination of these styles creates a certain spirit of negotiation that facilitates or obstructs agreement. Rathbun applies the argument to relations among France, Germany, and Great Britain during the 1920s as well as Palestinian-Israeli negotiations since the 1990s. His analysis, based on an intensive analysis of primary documents, shows how different diplomatic styles can successfully resolve apparently intractable dilemmas and equally, how they can thwart agreements that were seemingly within reach.  afunded by Knowledge Unlatched  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aInternational relations. 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.  adiplomacy and foreign affairs, international relation theories, theory of diplomacy, diplomatic styles, coercive bargaining, reasoned dialogue, pragmatic statecraft, psychology of negotiation, psychology of leaders, palestine and isreal.2 aKnowledge Unlatchedefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9780801455063?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801455063423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801455063/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles